WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.700
I want to start with a bit of a story.

00:00:02.700 --> 00:00:08.680
It's a story that happened in 1989, about 1,400 miles up the coast of where we sit now

00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:12.400
in Seattle near Anchorage, Alaska.

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:17.520
The Exxon Valdez was carrying 53 million gallons of crude oil when it left port in the middle

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:20.040
of the night.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:23.000
Many of you know where this is going.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:30.180
At around 11.25 p.m., the ship deviated from a predetermined shipping lane to try and skirt

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:33.320
some icebergs that were in the water.

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:37.419
There was only a single officer on duty for most of the night.

00:00:37.419 --> 00:00:40.040
This was in violation of company policy.

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:45.799
But shifts were long, people were tired, and that's what it was.

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:52.360
Around midnight, this officer decided it was time to move back into the shipping lanes.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:58.279
He woke up a lookout, and the lookout said that there's a reef buoy that was on the right

00:00:58.279 --> 00:01:00.360
side of the ship instead of the left.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:01.360
This was bad.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:05.519
It meant that they went where they thought they were.

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:11.279
An immediate course change was ordered, but four minutes later, the ship had run aground,

00:01:11.279 --> 00:01:16.300
resulting in one of the worst environmental disasters of the 20th century.

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:19.599
I wanted to start with this story because I think it illustrates a phrase that a lot

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:28.480
of us encounter a lot and are familiar with, and that is the ship is too big to turn.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.239
I think we hear it in the code we write, be it the languages we work in, maybe packages

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:36.919
we're developing, frameworks we're using.

00:01:36.919 --> 00:01:42.559
Sometimes we hear it about the sector we work in, be it academia or government or industry,

00:01:42.559 --> 00:01:47.379
and often we hear it about the places we work, so the teams we work in or the companies or

00:01:47.379 --> 00:01:51.419
the organizations we're at.

00:01:51.419 --> 00:01:57.419
And yeah, momentum is a strong force, but turning the ship in time is possible, and

00:01:57.419 --> 00:02:02.099
I want to talk through some of the lessons learned, both successes and challenges, in

00:02:02.099 --> 00:02:07.860
working through the process of trying to modernize or start to modernize our data science toolkit

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:12.139
over the last one and a half years at KSR, which is a market research company that I

00:02:12.139 --> 00:02:14.259
work at.

00:02:14.259 --> 00:02:19.179
Every organization is different, but hopefully pieces of this are useful in thinking about

00:02:19.179 --> 00:02:23.660
kick-starting change at wherever you may work.

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:30.139
When we were deciding to try and figure out which pieces of this we wanted to tackle and

00:02:30.139 --> 00:02:35.179
how we wanted to turn the ship, we sort of used these three guiding principles of clear

00:02:35.179 --> 00:02:40.520
navigation, managing expectations and sort of understanding the ship that you're in,

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:47.119
and then also finding and thinking about supporting the right crew to make the turn.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:52.119
I want to back up for just a second, though, and talk about what real-world impacts and

00:02:52.119 --> 00:02:55.880
end-to-end data science means at KSR.

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:01.320
So we're a 40-year-old market research company, and I think market research can have impacts

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:06.600
on the real world and our day-to-day lives in a variety of ways.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:11.679
I chose three examples that are food-based, because I like to eat, we're in a great food

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:13.679
city here in Seattle.

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.779
The first is price, and I think a good example of this is the recent Chipotle shrinkflation

00:03:18.779 --> 00:03:24.199
gate that folks might be familiar with, where Chipotle was charging the same amount of money

00:03:24.199 --> 00:03:28.440
for a burrito, but offering less stuff in it.

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:34.380
These pricing decisions by companies are often made as a result of market research.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:36.199
The second is availability.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:41.839
So those of you that were around in the 90s might remember Altoid Sours or Choco Tacos,

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:46.639
things that you can't get anymore, maybe if you go on eBay, I don't know.

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:53.960
But the availability of products that companies sell is also determined often by market research.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:56.240
And finally, the types of products available.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:00.199
So this is the reason you can't get poutine at a McDonald's here in the U.S., but you

00:04:00.199 --> 00:04:06.600
go up the road a bit in Canada, and you can get gravy on your fries.

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:12.759
So I work on the Decision Sciences and Innovation team at KSNR, and we touch end-to-end data

00:04:12.759 --> 00:04:16.600
science in sort of three main ways, or three pillars.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:18.440
The first is survey design.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:23.040
So this is how we collect our data, and it involves components like web development,

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:29.440
data wrangling pipelines, the language of the web, and also experimental design.

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:31.239
This is sort of our bread and butter.

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:34.519
We develop statistical models and simulations for our client.

00:04:34.519 --> 00:04:39.700
We run market research-specific analyses, so things like conjoint and segmentation,

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:47.640
and also more traditional data science analyses, so folks may be familiar with, like A-B testing.

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:53.679
We also touch the reporting side of things at KSNR, mostly through data visualization,

00:04:53.679 --> 00:05:00.559
generating summary data for our reporting teams to use, and also a variety of web applications,

00:05:00.559 --> 00:05:06.040
mostly in Shiny, that allow our clients to interactively sort of work with and understand

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:09.880
the data that we've collected in the surveys and the simulations and the models that we've

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:10.880
built.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:17.640
DSI also has a variety of internal initiatives that spans these areas, so things like automation,

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:22.000
codebase refactoring and updates, and AI initiatives.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.480
So back to turning the ship.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:31.160
I came on at KSNR about a year and a half ago, and I think one of the things we talked

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:37.959
about when we were defining my job responsibilities and what the plan was for the next year was

00:05:37.959 --> 00:05:42.880
thinking about the areas that we wanted to turn the ship in, but also why we're trying

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:48.640
to modernize the toolkit at KSNR, and I think those whys fall into three main buckets.

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:53.200
The first is that statistical rigor doesn't always equal optimized code, right?

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.959
KSNR has a foundation of really building strong math behind our data analyses over the 40

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:03.839
years that the company's been in existence, but things have changed, right?

00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:08.000
And we can now optimize code for a lot of different things, so for speed, for understandability

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.000
and modularity, and so that was one of the big sort of reasons why we want to try and

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.279
upgrade things.

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:20.200
The second is that we offer data products that are software.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:26.279
A lot of that are the shiny apps that we develop, but also automated reports as well, and we

00:06:26.279 --> 00:06:33.320
can apply some basic but modern software development practices to improve the consistency and the

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:37.160
functionality of those products.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:39.640
And finally, the evolution of the field.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:40.920
Things have just changed, right?

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:43.720
Things have changed a lot in 40 years, period.

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:47.720
Things have changed a lot in data science over the last decade and the languages that

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:48.720
we work in.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:54.959
There are a lot of new tools to bring to bear that can help us generate better work.

00:06:54.959 --> 00:06:59.519
So back to our guiding principles, we'll start with clear navigation.

00:06:59.519 --> 00:07:04.160
For us, finding clear navigation was made up of three parts.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:09.760
The first is identifying strengths and then figuring out ways to amplify them.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:15.399
The second is identifying weaknesses, patching the big holes and understanding where on sort

00:07:15.399 --> 00:07:20.679
of the trade-off axis projects are.

00:07:20.679 --> 00:07:26.000
And lastly, trying to understand our audience, and often for that, it was our internal team.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.079
For us, that's an organization that uses different languages and tools to do the work that we

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:38.359
do, and a lot of embedded processes and history that come along with that.

00:07:38.359 --> 00:07:43.079
For each of these guiding principles, I want to provide a short case study that sort of

00:07:43.079 --> 00:07:46.320
dives in a little bit on how we applied them.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:48.440
The first is our migration to GitHub.

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:54.079
So this happened right when I came on board, or shortly thereafter, and we decided this

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:58.480
was a high-priority thing to try and work on.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:01.200
So we identified some strengths on our team.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.279
The team had a great history of collaboration and communication.

00:08:04.279 --> 00:08:06.220
We had good IT support.

00:08:06.220 --> 00:08:11.779
We identified a really, I think, big hole that we wanted to patch, which is this unsustainable

00:08:11.779 --> 00:08:18.779
version control that was going on that might work great for Word documents and PowerPoints,

00:08:18.779 --> 00:08:25.739
or maybe just work okay for those, but does not work for multiple Shiny apps.

00:08:25.739 --> 00:08:27.380
But we needed to think of our audience.

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:32.419
DSI, our team, had a lot of skills, has a lot of skills, but they were mostly unfamiliar

00:08:32.419 --> 00:08:34.659
with GitHub.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:39.619
So I think this migration has ongoing challenges and successes.

00:08:39.619 --> 00:08:40.619
Setup took time.

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:45.419
We had to write documentation, we had to coordinate with IT, and we had a boatload of legacy code

00:08:45.419 --> 00:08:47.179
to migrate.

00:08:47.179 --> 00:08:50.140
But for us, the successes have outweighed the costs.

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:54.739
So now we have more than 200 repositories, and we have really strong engagement across

00:08:54.739 --> 00:08:57.820
the team with the project management tools.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:03.059
GitHub has also allowed us to take some of the burden off IT and make it easier for them

00:09:03.059 --> 00:09:06.299
to deploy client-facing tools for us.

00:09:06.299 --> 00:09:07.380
And we're not finished, right?

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:11.179
There's still a lot of work to do, ongoing training on sort of more intermediate and

00:09:11.179 --> 00:09:18.739
advanced use of GitHub on our team, and integration across more teams at KSNR.

00:09:18.739 --> 00:09:22.419
On to managing expectations.

00:09:22.419 --> 00:09:25.539
So for us, this is composed of four pieces.

00:09:25.539 --> 00:09:30.179
Thinking about leadership's expectations versus your expectations, I think often those two

00:09:30.179 --> 00:09:34.260
things are different, and finding alignment is really important, or was really important

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.539
for us.

00:09:36.539 --> 00:09:39.140
The second is thinking about on-the-job learning.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:43.380
It's something that takes time and often needs to be balanced with the business needs of

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:46.260
the organization.

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:49.020
There's also no sea change frequently, right?

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:54.580
Change may be slower than you or your colleagues or leadership would like.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:58.619
And finally, developing a strong business case is something that's been really successful

00:09:58.619 --> 00:09:59.619
for us.

00:09:59.619 --> 00:10:04.580
It's having multiple people in the company on multiple levels, being able to understand

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:10.820
the benefits of the change that you're trying to initiate.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:15.020
So this is an example of something I was really excited to try and change when I first came

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:20.619
on board, and that is an entrenched data pipeline at KSNR.

00:10:20.619 --> 00:10:27.020
So often, we'll take that survey data from a platform we use, it gets manually migrated

00:10:27.020 --> 00:10:28.900
to in-house storage.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:32.500
We have some folks that do some data wrangling in SPSS.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:36.020
We have some folks that do some more data wrangling in Excel, and eventually we come

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:40.859
up with summarized data that gets used in reporting.

00:10:40.859 --> 00:10:48.940
I was really excited to change this initially, and move to our, you know, an open-source

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:54.320
language with benefits that I think most folks in this room know and understand, and also

00:10:54.320 --> 00:11:00.919
leverage some of our API use to pull the data live from our survey platform.

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:06.820
To me, there were really clear benefits to this modification, but there were also risks

00:11:06.820 --> 00:11:09.559
and complications.

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:16.320
So this pipeline had a bunch of existing processes and automation attached to it, and they were

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:17.320
really mature.

00:11:17.320 --> 00:11:21.599
They're processes that have been going on at the company for a really long time.

00:11:21.599 --> 00:11:25.280
And there's a lot of business reliance on those processes.

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:30.159
And it's really important that they operate quickly and efficiently and correctly.

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:34.880
So I think that the business case for this was solid, but maybe a little misguided.

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:43.239
And I think that once we had some conversations internally, and applied some of those components

00:11:43.239 --> 00:11:47.599
of managing expectations, it became clear that this wasn't the right time to try and

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:48.840
change this.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:52.719
And it's something that, you know, I think is on the docket for us for the next couple

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:53.719
of years.

00:11:53.719 --> 00:11:57.080
So maybe the ship is a little slower to turn here.

00:11:57.080 --> 00:12:00.840
Finally, the right crew.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:04.039
I think one thing I learned in the last year and a half is that networking doesn't stop

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:05.039
when you enter an organization.

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:07.559
I think a lot of people probably know this.

00:12:07.559 --> 00:12:09.559
It was new to me.

00:12:09.559 --> 00:12:13.039
And the allies and champions that can see the value in what you're trying to do are

00:12:13.039 --> 00:12:15.039
really golden.

00:12:15.239 --> 00:12:19.520
Yes, learning equals growth and development.

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:24.080
But it also introduces new skills to the mix that can help turn things on an organizational

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:27.719
level, sometimes in unexpected ways.

00:12:27.719 --> 00:12:31.679
And I think we've also spent a lot of time thinking about our future crew.

00:12:31.679 --> 00:12:34.059
The crew is going to change.

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:38.760
And so doing work to try and future proof our processes and documentation was really

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:41.520
important to us.

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:46.880
And I just want to highlight a partnership that I think is illustrative of the right

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:48.679
crew.

00:12:48.679 --> 00:12:55.039
When I first came on, my perception was that the circles of the Venn diagram of our team

00:12:55.039 --> 00:12:58.200
at DSI and our IT team were really separate.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:01.239
There wasn't a lot of overlap.

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:04.039
Most of our communication was request-based.

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:07.140
I need this from you, you need this from me.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:12.299
We spoke different languages to some extent, and there were a few shared goals.

00:13:12.299 --> 00:13:17.340
I think in the last year and a half, we've made a lot of progress in this partnership

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:18.500
with IT.

00:13:18.500 --> 00:13:21.179
I think that language gap has been reduced quite a bit.

00:13:21.179 --> 00:13:25.500
We've improved our processes, and things feel really collaborative now.

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:29.460
I think part of that is finding overlapping goals, and it's been really exciting to co-develop

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:35.539
infrastructure with the support and input of IT.

00:13:35.539 --> 00:13:42.299
A lot of the, I think, the adoption of new tools helped spur a lot of this partnership.

00:13:42.299 --> 00:13:48.460
So when I first came on, we were just starting to use Posit Connect and Workbench, which

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:51.299
took a lot of the burden off of our IT team.

00:13:51.299 --> 00:13:56.380
It was easier to deploy apps to our clients, and we had really stable development environments

00:13:56.380 --> 00:13:57.739
to work in.

00:13:57.739 --> 00:14:03.099
The GitHub migration was also a strong collaborative effort, and also documentation.

00:14:03.099 --> 00:14:08.859
I think, again, thinking about that future crew is great, but it was also super helpful

00:14:08.859 --> 00:14:14.140
from IT's perspective, from a certification standpoint, which is a core component of their

00:14:14.140 --> 00:14:16.500
responsibilities.

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:21.780
For us, we have adopted Cordo-based documentation, which has been a game-changer in the last

00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:22.780
year.

00:14:22.780 --> 00:14:28.539
There's way more transparency, it's easy to build living documents, and the version control

00:14:28.539 --> 00:14:31.500
of documentation has been fantastic.

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:38.580
So I've talked a little bit about how we did it and things we thought about, but it's also

00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:39.580
had impact.

00:14:39.580 --> 00:14:46.020
I think a big one is more transparent collaboration and project management.

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:50.780
A lot of this is GitHub, but implementing things like code review, project management

00:14:50.780 --> 00:14:54.820
that lives alongside code, and long-term tracking of issues has been really, really helpful

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:57.260
for us.

00:14:57.260 --> 00:15:00.580
We've worked to implement a lot of efficiency improvements.

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:06.380
So again, updating that code base with some more modularity, the adoption of APIs in our

00:15:06.380 --> 00:15:11.099
work, and also building internal R packages gives folks more time to be creative in the

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:14.940
things that they're doing and the work they're building for our clients.

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:19.979
And finally, those same new things have also opened a lot of new work streams for us, which

00:15:19.979 --> 00:15:22.940
has been really exciting.

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:30.059
So we've started the turn early at KSNR, and it's had impact.

00:15:30.059 --> 00:15:31.700
For us, it's a moving target.

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:38.140
We definitely have a long way to go, but we've tried to start to turn the ship with a couple

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:40.979
of strategies that I've talked about here.

00:15:40.979 --> 00:15:45.380
Hopefully this has been helpful in sparking some ideas for implementing change in wherever

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:47.460
you may work.

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:49.820
I'm happy to connect.

00:15:49.820 --> 00:15:53.739
Please reach out if you want to chat more about data science and market research, what

00:15:53.739 --> 00:15:58.099
we do at KSNR, or really anything at all related.

00:15:58.099 --> 00:15:59.099
Thanks.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:00.140
Thank you.

00:16:06.140 --> 00:16:07.140
All right.

00:16:07.140 --> 00:16:08.940
So we have a couple of questions from Slido.

00:16:08.940 --> 00:16:09.940
Great.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:13.299
The first one is, data science isn't the same as software engineering.

00:16:13.299 --> 00:16:17.780
Do you have any tips or techniques for doing test-driven development when working with

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:18.780
data?

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:19.780
Yeah.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:24.059
I think it's a really good point.

00:16:24.059 --> 00:16:28.419
I think part of it, and maybe this isn't totally answering the question, but I think part of

00:16:28.739 --> 00:16:32.739
it is making those relationships and collaboration, right?

00:16:32.739 --> 00:16:35.820
I think it's really hard to be good at everything.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:39.820
And so finding folks that are good at the software development, are willing to work

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:45.539
with you and sort of help implement that at your organization, I think is the best strategy.

00:16:45.539 --> 00:16:52.299
I think there's also a variety of really good tools, particularly in the R ecosystem that

00:16:52.299 --> 00:16:57.460
I'm more familiar with, in doing sort of more test-driven work.

00:16:57.500 --> 00:16:58.500
So things like TestDot.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:16:59.500
Yeah.

00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:01.500
All right.

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:05.219
Do you have any tips for people who are migrating their teams to GitHub?

00:17:05.219 --> 00:17:07.579
Because that migration could be a pretty big lift.

00:17:07.579 --> 00:17:08.579
Yeah.

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:15.739
I think for us, training was really huge and sort of building, making sure we were building

00:17:15.739 --> 00:17:20.219
in enough time to do that training effectively.

00:17:20.219 --> 00:17:26.099
And then I think the other piece of it is to go slow when you need to.

00:17:26.099 --> 00:17:32.180
So work slowly on things that maybe are not high stakes at first to move, so you can work

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:36.219
out all the kinks when you get to the important stuff.

00:17:36.219 --> 00:17:37.219
Great.

00:17:37.219 --> 00:17:42.380
Where do you host your Cordo documents?

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:45.619
Is it on GitHub Pages or where do you do it internally?

00:17:45.619 --> 00:17:47.780
Yeah, we had some debate.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:48.780
That's a really good question.

00:17:48.780 --> 00:17:55.099
We had some debate on this and, you know, the code base for a given process document

00:17:55.099 --> 00:17:57.380
in Cordo lives on GitHub.

00:17:57.380 --> 00:18:00.219
So people can add it, use and modify it dynamically.

00:18:00.219 --> 00:18:06.699
Ultimately, the end documents that get rendered live in a team's folder on our organization.

00:18:06.699 --> 00:18:10.380
So it's somebody's job, right, to, when there are updates, update that HTML file in the

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:11.619
team's folder.

00:18:11.619 --> 00:18:16.099
And that's just following sort of, you know, years of history about where things are expected

00:18:16.099 --> 00:18:17.099
to live in the company.

00:18:19.099 --> 00:18:20.099
All right.

00:18:20.099 --> 00:18:22.099
I think we have time for one more.

00:18:23.099 --> 00:18:25.099
Second.

00:18:31.099 --> 00:18:35.099
How do you best recognize when to start turning the ship?

00:18:35.099 --> 00:18:37.099
Yeah, I think it's really hard, right?

00:18:37.099 --> 00:18:41.699
And not to lean into the metaphor too hard, but, like, they didn't know it was too late

00:18:41.699 --> 00:18:44.780
to turn until it was too late to turn, right?

00:18:44.780 --> 00:18:50.619
So I think that, like, thinking about that second part about expectations is really important

00:18:50.619 --> 00:18:56.300
and understanding your ship and sort of how agile you need to turn.

00:18:56.300 --> 00:19:01.300
How agile your ship and how able your team is to turn is part of it.

00:19:01.300 --> 00:19:07.819
I think the other piece is a gradual turn over a longer period of time is always going

00:19:07.819 --> 00:19:10.819
to be better than a frantic turn at the end, right?

00:19:10.819 --> 00:19:15.420
So sort of thinking long term and building in updates and modernization along the way

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:17.619
is great if you can do it.

00:19:18.619 --> 00:19:19.619
All right.

00:19:19.619 --> 00:19:22.619
Well, it's time we have for you, so let's thank Keaton again for his talk.

00:19:22.619 --> 00:19:23.619
Thank you.

00:19:23.619 --> 00:19:24.619
Thank you.

00:19:24.619 --> 00:19:25.619
Thank you.

00:19:25.619 --> 00:19:26.619
Thank you.

00:19:26.619 --> 00:19:27.619
Thank you.

